00:47:32,767 --> 00:47:35,227
Back when you asked me
to teach you sign language.

783
00:47:37,188 --> 00:47:38,647
INTRO TO KOREAN SIGN LANGUAGE

784
00:47:38,731 --> 00:47:40,483
Okay, fine.

785
00:47:41,484 --> 00:47:42,485
But…

786
00:47:43,569 --> 00:47:44,528
under one condition.

787
00:47:44,612 --> 00:47:45,654
Sure.

788
00:47:45,738 --> 00:47:47,698
Just once in your life,

789
00:47:48,491 --> 00:47:50,743
grant me a favor, no matter what I ask.

790
00:47:50,826 --> 00:47:52,036
A favor?

791
00:47:52,953 --> 00:47:53,829
Pinky promise.

792
00:47:54,497 --> 00:47:55,373
Okay.

793
00:48:01,003 --> 00:48:02,421
I'm asking that favor now.

794
00:48:04,632 --> 00:48:06,384
- Seol-a.
- I said, "no matter what."

795
00:48:09,303 --> 00:48:13,099
There are medical ethics
that you follow as a doctor,

796
00:48:13,724 --> 00:48:15,976
- and as a lawyer, I--
- "Just once in your life."

797
00:48:17,353 --> 00:48:18,437
"No matter what."

798
00:48:19,688 --> 00:48:21,399
You always said it yourself

799
00:48:21,482 --> 00:48:23,401
that the law isn't always just.

800
00:48:25,152 --> 00:48:27,446
You saw what my brother-in-law did.

801
00:48:28,072 --> 00:48:30,366
Just thinking about it
makes my blood boil.

802
00:48:30,991 --> 00:48:33,994
If I had known,
I'd have beaten him to a pulp too.

803
00:48:35,037 --> 00:48:37,415
Is it justice for Seol-yeon
to go to prison for that?

804
00:48:37,498 --> 00:48:39,417
Is that what you call justice?

805
00:48:56,725 --> 00:48:58,185
It's been ten minutes.

806
00:48:58,269 --> 00:48:59,270
If it's hard to say…

807
00:48:59,353 --> 00:49:00,771
It was voluntary intoxication.

808
00:49:01,564 --> 00:49:02,940
Sorry?

809
00:49:04,733 --> 00:49:06,318
Han Seol-yeon's assault case.

810
00:49:06,944 --> 00:49:08,988
Ms. Han took the medication on purpose.

811
00:49:10,156 --> 00:49:12,616
She knew the medication
would make her violent,

812
00:49:12,700 --> 00:49:16,287
and she took it on purpose
to fight back against her husband.

813
00:49:16,996 --> 00:49:18,038
Did she say that herself?

814
00:49:19,415 --> 00:49:20,416
Yes.

815
00:49:20,916 --> 00:49:22,334
She probably didn't realize

816
00:49:22,418 --> 00:49:25,004
this would work against her.

817
00:49:25,713 --> 00:49:27,006
Who else knows about this?

818
00:49:27,089 --> 00:49:28,716
No one yet.

819
00:49:28,799 --> 00:49:30,092
Why did you tell me?

820
00:49:30,718 --> 00:49:31,969
I'm confused.

821
00:49:34,221 --> 00:49:35,639
I don't know what to do.

822
00:49:36,265 --> 00:49:39,185
I have no intention of micromanaging
a junior lawyer's ethics.

823
00:49:40,019 --> 00:49:42,605
I'll pretend I didn't hear that,
so you decide.

824
00:49:42,688 --> 00:49:44,398
If I could've made a decision--

825
00:49:44,482 --> 00:49:45,483
You would have.

826
00:49:49,820 --> 00:49:51,655
Then let me tell you my perspective.

827
00:49:52,323 --> 00:49:53,699
To me,

828
00:49:54,325 --> 00:49:56,994
justice means protecting the people
I have to protect.

829
00:49:57,995 --> 00:49:59,747
And for that, I'd do anything.

830
00:50:00,915 --> 00:50:03,250
Even if it's something illegal?

831
00:50:04,001 --> 00:50:05,669
As a lawyer, it would be wrong.

832
00:50:05,753 --> 00:50:08,005
Within the bounds of the law, of course.

833
00:50:12,176 --> 00:50:15,471
But if it's a loophole disguised
as legality, then I won't hold back.

834
00:50:21,936 --> 00:50:24,355
Don't think like a small mind
trapped in dogma.

835
00:50:25,272 --> 00:50:26,815
Try to see the bigger picture.

836
00:50:37,576 --> 00:50:38,452
Seol-a.

837
00:50:39,411 --> 00:50:41,288
Let's meet at Seol-yeon's house.

838
00:50:41,372 --> 00:50:42,248
Okay.

839
00:50:50,631 --> 00:50:52,424
You can never tell anyone

840
00:50:52,508 --> 00:50:54,760
what you told us.

841
00:50:54,843 --> 00:50:56,053
- Okay?
- Okay.

842
00:50:56,595 --> 00:50:57,930
Not the prosecutor

843
00:50:58,013 --> 00:50:59,431
or your doctor.

844
00:50:59,515 --> 00:51:00,474
No one.

845
00:51:00,558 --> 00:51:01,600
Okay.

846
00:51:03,269 --> 00:51:05,563
Do you still have the security camera?

847
00:51:07,439 --> 00:51:08,315
Yes.

848
00:51:08,399 --> 00:51:09,817
Where's the video?

849
00:51:11,944 --> 00:51:13,028
In my cell phone.

850
00:51:16,240 --> 00:51:17,658
I'll take this.

851
00:51:19,076 --> 00:51:22,538
You can withhold statements
that may be used against you,

852
00:51:22,621 --> 00:51:24,081
but you can't give false testimony.

853
00:51:24,164 --> 00:51:25,499
Okay.

854
00:51:25,583 --> 00:51:28,043
If you're asked a question
that could hurt your case,

855
00:51:28,127 --> 00:51:30,462
you can exercise
your right to remain silent.

856
00:51:31,213 --> 00:51:33,507
Okay. I won't lie.

857
00:51:40,180 --> 00:51:42,099
HUSBAND ASSAULT CASE
SECOND HEARING

858
00:51:42,182 --> 00:51:44,184
Case number 2025-Gohap-250916.

859
00:51:44,268 --> 00:51:46,270
The court is now in session.

860
00:51:46,353 --> 00:51:49,857
The results of the evaluation
requested by the defense have arrived.

861
00:51:50,482 --> 00:51:51,984
What's your opinion, Counsel?

862
00:51:52,610 --> 00:51:54,612
As seen in the evaluation report,

863
00:51:54,695 --> 00:51:57,448
the defendant completely lost the ability

864
00:51:57,531 --> 00:51:59,158
to distinguish right from wrong

865
00:51:59,241 --> 00:52:01,869
or to make decisions
after taking the prescribed medication.

866
00:52:02,953 --> 00:52:05,831
She has no memory
of what happened during the 30 minutes

867
00:52:05,914 --> 00:52:07,791
after taking the medication.

868
00:52:08,292 --> 00:52:11,128
As noted in the report,
the drug's side effects likely suppressed

869
00:52:11,211 --> 00:52:12,838
frontal lobe function,

870
00:52:12,921 --> 00:52:14,798
leading to violent behavior.

871
00:52:15,424 --> 00:52:19,219
Therefore, the assault in question
was not the result

872
00:52:19,303 --> 00:52:21,930
of the defendant's free will,

873
00:52:22,014 --> 00:52:25,267
and she should be found not guilty
by reason of mental incapacity.

874
00:52:25,893 --> 00:52:26,852
As previously requested,

875
00:52:26,935 --> 00:52:29,355
we will now proceed
with the questioning of the evaluator.

876
00:52:29,438 --> 00:52:31,106
I'll allow it.

877
00:52:32,900 --> 00:52:34,068
On May 29,

878
00:52:34,151 --> 00:52:37,988
did you observe the defendant's condition
after she took her psychiatric medication?

879
00:52:38,072 --> 00:52:39,448
Yes.

880
00:52:39,531 --> 00:52:40,491
WITNESS

881
00:52:41,700 --> 00:52:44,453
Your Honor, this is
the footage recorded that day.

882
00:52:58,008 --> 00:52:59,510
How can she not remember that?

883
00:53:01,887 --> 00:53:03,347
She looks out of her mind.

884
00:53:05,849 --> 00:53:07,434
Look how she threw the pillow.

885
00:53:15,359 --> 00:53:16,985
How was the defendant during this period?

886
00:53:17,069 --> 00:53:18,529
She was in a blackout state,

887
00:53:18,612 --> 00:53:21,907
and she showed impulsive behavior
and extreme violence.

888
00:53:21,990 --> 00:53:24,702
Have other patients ever displayed

889
00:53:24,785 --> 00:53:28,205
violence or aggressive behavior
during blackouts?

890
00:53:28,288 --> 00:53:30,082
No, they haven't.

891
00:53:30,165 --> 00:53:33,043
Ms. Han Seol-yeon
is a highly unusual case.

892
00:53:33,127 --> 00:53:34,503
Could you elaborate?

893
00:53:34,586 --> 00:53:37,256
We performed a brain MRI
to analyze changes

894
00:53:37,339 --> 00:53:39,299
in Ms. Han's brain activity.

895
00:53:39,383 --> 00:53:40,592
BEFORE & AFTER MEDICATION

896
00:53:40,676 --> 00:53:43,554
The top scan is Ms. Han's usual brain MRI.

897
00:53:43,637 --> 00:53:45,013
And the bottom one

898
00:53:45,097 --> 00:53:49,101
is the brain MRI taken
after she took the prescribed medication.

899
00:53:49,727 --> 00:53:53,063
That area marked in red

900
00:53:53,188 --> 00:53:56,525
is the front part of the frontal lobe,
the prefrontal cortex.

901
00:53:57,151 --> 00:54:00,738
This area controls emotions,
suppresses impulses,

902
00:54:00,821 --> 00:54:02,865
and helps with social judgment.

903
00:54:03,991 --> 00:54:06,702
Many experts refer
to the prefrontal cortex

904
00:54:06,785 --> 00:54:09,037
as the brain's braking system.

905
00:54:09,121 --> 00:54:14,168
In other words, the prefrontal cortex
controls and regulates

906
00:54:14,251 --> 00:54:17,921
aggressive or impulsive behavior.

907
00:54:18,005 --> 00:54:19,173
I see.

908
00:54:19,256 --> 00:54:22,801
But it was confirmed
that the defendant's frontal lobe activity

909
00:54:22,885 --> 00:54:26,722
dropped noticeably
after taking the medication.

910
00:54:27,765 --> 00:54:29,099
As you can see,

911
00:54:29,183 --> 00:54:33,187
the area that should appear
bright looks faded.

912
00:54:33,979 --> 00:54:38,859
It means the defendant's frontal lobe
was not functioning properly.

913
00:54:39,485 --> 00:54:40,486
What does that mean?

914
00:54:41,862 --> 00:54:45,491
It's presumed that the suppressed function

915
00:54:45,574 --> 00:54:46,742
led to her aggression.

916
00:54:48,035 --> 00:54:49,203
I see.

917
00:54:50,746 --> 00:54:51,663
No further questions.

918
00:54:56,001 --> 00:54:56,877
Defendant,

919
00:54:57,795 --> 00:55:00,464
can you tell us your first
and last memories from that day?

920
00:55:01,256 --> 00:55:05,427
I was watching my favorite show,
which ends at 11 p.m.,

921
00:55:05,511 --> 00:55:07,012
and I fell asleep.

922
00:55:08,138 --> 00:55:10,474
Next thing I know,

923
00:55:11,558 --> 00:55:13,727
I was handcuffed in a holding cell.

924
00:55:17,689 --> 00:55:19,817
Do you not remember anything at all?

925
00:55:19,900 --> 00:55:21,026
No, I don't.

926
00:55:21,109 --> 00:55:23,529
According to the police,
once the cuffs were on,

927
00:55:23,612 --> 00:55:26,156
you asked if you could take the handbag

928
00:55:26,240 --> 00:55:27,449
that was on the table.

929
00:55:31,119 --> 00:55:33,247
They're trying to frame it
as diminished capacity.

930
00:55:33,330 --> 00:55:34,540
It looks like it.

931
00:55:49,096 --> 00:55:53,350
Case number 2025-Gohap-250916.

932
00:55:54,226 --> 00:55:57,396
Defendant Han Seol-yeon,
the court will now deliver the verdict.

933
00:56:04,987 --> 00:56:06,947
The defendant is found not guilty.

934
00:56:16,039 --> 00:56:18,625
The summary of this ruling
is hereby announced.

935
00:56:26,884 --> 00:56:29,344
A toast to the great Kang Hyo-min

936
00:56:29,428 --> 00:56:31,722
and to Yoon Seok-hoon,
who isn't with us today

937
00:56:31,805 --> 00:56:34,433
but helped make that acquittal happen!

938
00:56:34,516 --> 00:56:36,018
Cheers!

939
00:56:36,101 --> 00:56:37,686
- Cheers!
- Cheers!

940
00:56:44,943 --> 00:56:46,737
- That video…
- Yes?

941
00:56:47,863 --> 00:56:49,281
Did you delete it?

942
00:56:49,364 --> 00:56:51,325
Not yet. I will.

943
00:56:51,408 --> 00:56:52,326
Really?

944
00:56:52,910 --> 00:56:54,953
Then before you erase it…

945
00:56:59,625 --> 00:57:00,834
<i>Hey!</i>

946
00:57:00,918 --> 00:57:03,378
<i>Your husband is home!</i>

947
00:57:07,007 --> 00:57:08,842
What are you doing at this hour?

948
00:57:10,844 --> 00:57:12,596
Can't you hear me?

949
00:57:12,679 --> 00:57:13,847
Say something.

950
00:57:15,641 --> 00:57:19,811
Why the heck are you eating at this hour?

951
00:57:20,312 --> 00:57:21,563
You look like a mess.

952
00:57:22,564 --> 00:57:23,982
Han Seol-yeon!

953
00:57:24,066 --> 00:57:25,359
Have you lost it?

954
00:57:26,109 --> 00:57:29,655
When someone asks you something,
you should answer!

955
00:57:41,708 --> 00:57:44,962
Be ready to go to hell,
you fucking bastard.

956
00:57:45,045 --> 00:57:48,632
I'll crush you just like you crushed me.

957
00:57:48,715 --> 00:57:49,758
You son of a bitch!

958
00:58:24,376 --> 00:58:25,919
Do we have <i>ramyeon </i>at home?

959
00:58:26,920 --> 00:58:28,088
I think so.

960
00:58:29,256 --> 00:58:31,550
Should I cook, or do you want to do it?

961
00:58:32,175 --> 00:58:33,468
I'll do it.

962
00:58:37,431 --> 00:58:38,640
What about beer?

963
00:58:39,349 --> 00:58:40,350
We don't have any.

964
00:58:46,648 --> 00:58:47,941
Where are you going?

965
00:58:48,025 --> 00:58:49,026
To get some beer.

966
00:58:50,402 --> 00:58:51,862
Get some chips too.

967
00:59:04,041 --> 00:59:06,293
Did I thank him?

968
00:59:22,893 --> 00:59:23,810
Who's there?

969
00:59:25,937 --> 00:59:27,022
Mr. Yoon.

970
00:59:27,647 --> 00:59:28,774
Where were you?

971
00:59:30,108 --> 00:59:31,276
I went to brush my teeth.

972
00:59:33,236 --> 00:59:34,571
I thought you weren't here.

973
00:59:35,280 --> 00:59:36,281
Is something wrong?

974
00:59:38,200 --> 00:59:41,828
I just realized
I didn't thank you properly earlier.

975
00:59:43,914 --> 00:59:45,248
Thank you.

976
00:59:45,874 --> 00:59:46,833
Okay.

977
00:59:48,168 --> 00:59:50,712
Did you come back to the office
just to say that?

978
00:59:50,796 --> 00:59:51,880
Yes.

979
00:59:51,963 --> 00:59:53,173
I thought you might be working

980
00:59:53,256 --> 00:59:54,925
on the construction company's
asset freeze.

981
00:59:55,008 --> 00:59:58,386
I was just wrapping up to go home.

982
00:59:59,262 --> 01:00:00,430
I see.

983
01:00:01,389 --> 01:00:02,265
See you tomorrow.

984
01:00:02,349 --> 01:00:03,225
Okay.

985
01:00:05,560 --> 01:00:06,436
Mr. Yoon.

986
01:00:10,690 --> 01:00:12,150
Would you like to have some beer?

987
01:00:15,862 --> 01:00:17,405
This is so nice!

988
01:00:19,658 --> 01:00:22,494
It's a shame
that we can't come up here often

989
01:00:22,577 --> 01:00:23,703
because of work.

990
01:00:28,542 --> 01:00:30,961
I really liked what you said.

991
01:00:32,129 --> 01:00:36,591
That justice is protecting
the people you have to protect.

992
01:00:39,636 --> 01:00:42,013
You told me last time

993
01:00:42,097 --> 01:00:47,602
that you realized how powerful
words can be as a weapon.

994
01:00:48,895 --> 01:00:52,899
So I realized
that you use that weapon carefully

995
01:00:53,525 --> 01:00:55,193
to defend your clients

996
01:00:56,319 --> 01:01:00,824
and to protect the people
you have to protect.

997
01:01:02,325 --> 01:01:04,953
I used to think the same way.

998
01:01:07,164 --> 01:01:09,457
Both my parents are in the legal field,

999
01:01:10,000 --> 01:01:11,626
so I naturally thought

1000
01:01:11,710 --> 01:01:14,004
I'd choose to become a lawyer.

1001
01:01:14,629 --> 01:01:16,590
But as a kid,

1002
01:01:16,673 --> 01:01:20,177
I saw my mom slicing her opponent
in court with such sharp words,

1003
01:01:20,260 --> 01:01:23,096
and I started to think
that maybe that path wasn't for me.

1004
01:01:23,722 --> 01:01:25,056
Then in high school,

1005
01:01:26,141 --> 01:01:28,894
my friend's dad got injured at work,

1006
01:01:28,977 --> 01:01:32,105
but the boss was so cruel
that he didn't even give him

1007
01:01:32,189 --> 01:01:33,940
any compensation or severance.

1008
01:01:35,025 --> 01:01:37,027
So I turned to my mom for help.

1009
01:01:38,612 --> 01:01:40,238
I wore my mom's clothes

1010
01:01:40,322 --> 01:01:42,240
and even copied the way she spoke.

1011
01:01:42,324 --> 01:01:43,783
As I talked to the boss,

1012
01:01:46,077 --> 01:01:47,329
I could see him flinch.

1013
01:01:47,829 --> 01:01:49,998
Even though I was only a high school kid.

1014
01:01:50,999 --> 01:01:52,334
That's when I realized

1015
01:01:53,043 --> 01:01:55,545
the sharpness of words isn't the problem.

1016
01:01:56,713 --> 01:01:59,174
What matters is where you use them

1017
01:01:59,716 --> 01:02:02,219
and who you use them for.

1018
01:02:02,844 --> 01:02:05,931
I realized that using words
to protect those I have to protect

1019
01:02:06,640 --> 01:02:08,725
could be a fun profession.

1020
01:02:09,517 --> 01:02:11,686
It felt like I was meant to do this.

1021
01:02:14,940 --> 01:02:16,483
You're meant to do this.

1022
01:02:16,566 --> 01:02:18,318
You're clearly cut out for the job.

1023
01:02:18,902 --> 01:02:19,986
I'm relieved to hear that.

1024
01:02:23,240 --> 01:02:24,407
I felt like…

1025
01:02:27,118 --> 01:02:29,996
I was walking through a dark tunnel alone,

1026
01:02:31,665 --> 01:02:33,541
but you lent me a flashlight.

1027
01:02:34,376 --> 01:02:35,710
Thank you.

1028
01:03:30,765 --> 01:03:33,852
BEYOND THE BAR

1029
01:03:33,935 --> 01:03:34,853
<i>A murder charge.</i>

1030
01:03:34,936 --> 01:03:36,938
Are they claiming
you intentionally killed him?

1031
01:03:37,022 --> 01:03:38,481
<i>I'm not suggesting we kill him.</i>

1032
01:03:38,565 --> 01:03:40,400
If he's dying anyway,
why not just let him?

1033
01:03:40,483 --> 01:03:43,862
<i>May I ask what you plan to indict her for?</i>

1034
01:03:43,945 --> 01:03:44,863
<i>Murder.</i>

1035
01:03:44,946 --> 01:03:48,325
<i>What if Dr. Choi was aware</i>
<i>of Kim Byeong-su's preexisting condition?</i>

1036
01:03:48,408 --> 01:03:49,617
- I found it.
- What?

1037
01:03:49,701 --> 01:03:50,660
Have you eaten anything?

1038
01:03:50,744 --> 01:03:53,204
<i>You must be that scary Boss Man.</i>

1039
01:03:53,288 --> 01:03:54,372
I was never scary.

1040
01:03:54,456 --> 01:03:57,000
I'm going to make Yullim
a place of justice.

1041
01:03:57,083 --> 01:03:59,377
<i>Find me Mr. Lee's weak spot.</i>

1042
01:03:59,461 --> 01:04:01,880
It appears we'll need
to fast-track the plan.

1043
